3
00:02:36,440 --> 00:02:39,080
<i>The hills are alive</i>

4
00:02:39,320 --> 00:02:43,560
<i>With the sound of music</i>

5
00:02:43,800 --> 00:02:46,160
<i>With songs they have sung</i>

6
00:02:46,400 --> 00:02:51,080
<i>For a thousand years</i>

7
00:02:51,320 --> 00:02:54,320
<i>The hills fill my heart</i>

8
00:02:54,560 --> 00:02:58,960
<i>With the sound of music</i>

9
00:02:59,200 --> 00:03:06,320
<i>My heart wants to sing</i>
<i>Every song it hears</i>

10
00:03:06,560 --> 00:03:11,200
<i>My heart wants to beat like the wings</i>
<i>Of the birds that rise</i>

11
00:03:11,440 --> 00:03:14,400
<i>From the lake to the trees</i>

12
00:03:14,640 --> 00:03:18,760
<i>My heart wants to sigh</i>
<i>Like a chime that flies</i>

13
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:22,800
<i>From a church on a breeze</i>

14
00:03:23,040 --> 00:03:26,400
<i>To laugh like a brook</i>
<i>When it trips and falls</i>

15
00:03:26,640 --> 00:03:30,000
<i>Over stones on its way</i>

16
00:03:30,240 --> 00:03:33,960
<i>To sing through the night</i>

17
00:03:34,200 --> 00:03:37,920
<i>Like a lark who is learning to pray</i>

18
00:03:38,160 --> 00:03:43,520
<i>I go to the hills</i>

19
00:03:43,760 --> 00:03:49,680
<i>When my heart is lonely</i>

20
00:03:49,920 --> 00:03:53,600
<i>I know I will hear</i>

21
00:03:53,840 --> 00:03:58,160
<i>What I've heard before</i>

22
00:03:58,400 --> 00:04:02,920
<i>My heart will be blessed</i>

23
00:04:03,160 --> 00:04:11,400
<i>With the sound of music</i>

24
00:04:11,640 --> 00:04:16,560
<i>And I'll sing...</i>

25
00:04:16,800 --> 00:04:26,880
<i>... once more</i>

26
00:08:55,920 --> 00:09:00,680
<i>Hallelujah, hallelujah</i>

27
00:09:00,920 --> 00:09:06,840
<i>Hallelujah, hallelujah</i>

28
00:09:07,640 --> 00:09:09,560
- Reverend Mother.
- Sister Bernice.

29
00:09:09,800 --> 00:09:13,120
- I simply cannot find her.
- Maria?

30
00:09:13,360 --> 00:09:15,200
She's missing again.

31
00:09:15,440 --> 00:09:17,760
We should've put a cowbell
around her neck.

32
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:20,920
Have you tried the barn? You know
how much she adores the animals.

33
00:09:21,160 --> 00:09:23,760
I have looked everywhere.
In all of the usual places.

34
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:26,160
Sister, considering it's Maria...

35
00:09:26,400 --> 00:09:30,400
...I suggest you look in someplace
unusual.

36
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:35,200
Well, Reverend Mother...

37
00:09:35,440 --> 00:09:37,960
...I hope this new infraction ends
whatever doubts...

38
00:09:38,200 --> 00:09:41,280
...you may still have
about Maria's future here.

39
00:09:41,520 --> 00:09:45,400
I always try to keep faith
in my doubts, Sister Berthe.

40
00:09:45,640 --> 00:09:48,400
After all, the wool of a black sheep
is just as warm.

41
00:09:48,640 --> 00:09:52,760
We are not talking about sheep,
black or white, Sister Margaretta.

42
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:56,280
Of all the candidates for
the novitiate, Maria is the least...

43
00:09:56,520 --> 00:09:59,160
Children, children.

44
00:09:59,400 --> 00:10:03,560
We were speculating about
the qualifications of our postulants.

45
00:10:03,800 --> 00:10:06,680
The Mistress of Novices
and the Mistress of Postulants...

46
00:10:06,920 --> 00:10:12,000
...were trying to help me
by expressing opposite points of view.

47
00:10:12,240 --> 00:10:15,120
Tell me, Sister Catherine,
what do you think of Maria?

48
00:10:15,360 --> 00:10:19,000
She's a wonderful girl,
some of the time.

49
00:10:19,240 --> 00:10:22,200
- Sister Agatha?
- It's very easy to like Maria...

50
00:10:22,440 --> 00:10:24,880
...except when it's difficult.

51
00:10:25,120 --> 00:10:28,520
- And you, Sister Sophia?
- Oh, I love her very dearly.

52
00:10:28,760 --> 00:10:31,560
But she always seems to be
in trouble, doesn't she?

53
00:10:31,800 --> 00:10:33,560
Exactly what I say.

54
00:10:33,800 --> 00:10:36,120
<i>She climbs a tree and scrapes her knee</i>

55
00:10:36,360 --> 00:10:38,360
<i>Her dress has got a tear</i>

56
00:10:38,600 --> 00:10:43,000
<i>She waltzes on her way to Mass</i>
<i>And whistles on the stair</i>

57
00:10:43,240 --> 00:10:47,560
<i>And underneath her wimple</i>
<i>She has curlers in her hair</i>

58
00:10:47,800 --> 00:10:52,200
<i>I've even heard her singing</i>
<i>In the abbey</i>

59
00:10:52,440 --> 00:10:54,320
<i>She's always late for chapel</i>

60
00:10:54,560 --> 00:10:56,800
<i>But her penitence is real</i>

61
00:10:57,040 --> 00:10:59,240
<i>She's always late for everything</i>

62
00:10:59,480 --> 00:11:01,560
<i>Except for every meal</i>

63
00:11:01,800 --> 00:11:06,280
<i>I hate to have to say it</i>
<i>But I very firmly feel</i>

64
00:11:06,520 --> 00:11:11,000
<i>Maria's not an asset to the abbey</i>

65
00:11:11,240 --> 00:11:13,680
<i>I'd like to say a word in her behalf</i>

66
00:11:13,920 --> 00:11:15,800
Say it, Sister Margaretta.

67
00:11:16,040 --> 00:11:21,320
<i>Maria makes me laugh</i>

68
00:11:22,640 --> 00:11:26,360
<i>How do you solve a problem like Maria?</i>

69
00:11:26,600 --> 00:11:30,280
<i>How do you catch a cloud</i>
<i>And pin it down?</i>

70
00:11:30,520 --> 00:11:34,000
<i>How do you find a word</i>
<i>That means Maria?</i>

71
00:11:34,240 --> 00:11:35,280
<i>A flibbertigibbet</i>

72
00:11:35,520 --> 00:11:38,320
<i>- A will-o'-the-wisp</i>
<i>- A clown</i>

73
00:11:38,400 --> 00:11:42,000
<i>Many a thing you know</i>
<i>You'd like to tell her</i>

74
00:11:42,240 --> 00:11:45,720
<i>Many a thing she ought to understand</i>

75
00:11:45,960 --> 00:11:49,800
<i>But how do you make her stay</i>
<i>And listen to all you say?</i>

76
00:11:50,040 --> 00:11:53,400
<i>How do you keep a wave upon the sand?</i>

77
00:11:53,640 --> 00:11:57,800
<i>How do you solve a problem like Maria?</i>

78
00:11:58,040 --> 00:12:03,320
<i>How do you hold a moonbeam...</i>

79
00:12:03,560 --> 00:12:09,600
<i>... in your hand?</i>

80
00:12:09,840 --> 00:12:13,200
<i>When I'm with her I'm confused</i>
<i>Out of focus and bemused</i>

81
00:12:13,440 --> 00:12:16,720
<i>And I never know exactly where I am</i>

82
00:12:16,960 --> 00:12:20,240
<i>- Unpredictable as weather</i>
<i>- She's as flighty as a feather</i>

83
00:12:20,480 --> 00:12:22,200
<i>- She's a darling</i>
<i>- She's a demon</i>

84
00:12:22,440 --> 00:12:23,880
<i>She's a lamb</i>

85
00:12:24,120 --> 00:12:27,600
<i>She'll out pester any pest</i>
<i>Drive a hornet from its nest</i>

86
00:12:27,840 --> 00:12:31,280
<i>She can throw a whirling dervish</i>
<i>Out of whirl</i>

87
00:12:31,520 --> 00:12:35,240
<i>- She is gentle, she is wild</i>
<i>- She's a riddle, she's a child</i>

88
00:12:35,480 --> 00:12:37,920
<i>- She's a headache</i>
<i>- She's an angel</i>

89
00:12:38,160 --> 00:12:42,400
<i>She's a girl</i>

90
00:12:42,640 --> 00:12:46,320
<i>How do you solve a problem like Maria?</i>

91
00:12:46,560 --> 00:12:50,160
<i>How do you catch a cloud</i>
<i>And pin it down?</i>

92
00:12:50,400 --> 00:12:53,800
<i>How do you find a word</i>
<i>That means Maria?</i>

93
00:12:54,040 --> 00:12:55,920
<i>- A flibbertigibbet</i>
<i>- A will-o'-the-wisp</i>

94
00:12:56,160 --> 00:12:57,960
<i>A clown</i>

95
00:12:58,200 --> 00:13:01,800
<i>Many a thing you know</i>
<i>You'd like to tell her</i>

96
00:13:02,040 --> 00:13:05,320
<i>Many a thing she ought to understand</i>

97
00:13:05,560 --> 00:13:09,760
<i>- But how do you make her stay</i>
<i>- And listen to all you say?</i>

98
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:13,880
<i>How do you keep a wave upon the sand?</i>

99
00:13:14,120 --> 00:13:19,680
<i>How do you solve a problem like Maria?</i>

100
00:13:35,000 --> 00:13:42,080
<i>How do you hold a moonbeam...</i>

101
00:13:42,320 --> 00:13:50,000
<i>... in your hand?</i>

102
00:13:59,840 --> 00:14:03,240
You may go in now, Maria.

103
00:14:13,840 --> 00:14:16,880
Come here, my child.

104
00:14:21,640 --> 00:14:23,600
Now sit down.

105
00:14:23,840 --> 00:14:27,280
Reverend Mother, I'm sorry.
I couldn't help myself.

106
00:14:27,520 --> 00:14:30,520
- The hills were beckoning and before...
- Dear.

107
00:14:30,760 --> 00:14:32,640
I haven't summoned you for apologies.

108
00:14:32,880 --> 00:14:35,400
Please let me ask for forgiveness.

109
00:14:35,640 --> 00:14:37,480
If you'll feel better.

110
00:14:37,720 --> 00:14:40,000
Yes, you see,
the sky was so blue today...

111
00:14:40,240 --> 00:14:43,880
...and everything was so green and
fragrant, I had to be a part of it.

112
00:14:44,120 --> 00:14:48,360
The Untersberg led me higher like
it wanted me to go through the clouds.

113
00:14:48,600 --> 00:14:50,600
Suppose darkness had come
and you were lost?

114
00:14:50,840 --> 00:14:53,000
Mother, I could never be lost
up there.

115
00:14:53,240 --> 00:14:55,920
That's my mountain.
I was brought up on it.

116
00:14:56,160 --> 00:14:57,800
It was the mountain that led me
to you.

117
00:14:58,040 --> 00:14:58,880
Oh?

118
00:14:59,120 --> 00:15:01,960
When I was a child,
I would come down and climb a tree...

119
00:15:02,200 --> 00:15:03,880
...and look in your garden.

120
00:15:04,120 --> 00:15:08,000
I'd see the sisters at work
and hear them sing.

121
00:15:08,240 --> 00:15:11,680
Which brings me to another
transgression, Reverend Mother.

122
00:15:11,920 --> 00:15:14,360
I was singing out there today.

123
00:15:14,600 --> 00:15:18,440
Only in the abbey do we have rules
about postulants singing.

124
00:15:18,680 --> 00:15:20,600
I can't stop wherever I am.

125
00:15:20,840 --> 00:15:23,080
Worse, I can't seem to stop
saying things.

126
00:15:23,320 --> 00:15:25,480
Everything I think and feel.

127
00:15:25,720 --> 00:15:27,080
Some call that "honesty".

128
00:15:27,320 --> 00:15:29,600
Oh, but it's terrible,
Reverend Mother!

129
00:15:29,840 --> 00:15:33,680
You know how Sister Berthe makes me
kiss the floor after a disagreement?

130
00:15:33,920 --> 00:15:38,760
Lately, I kiss the floor
when I see her coming to save time.

131
00:15:39,840 --> 00:15:41,680
Maria...

132
00:15:41,920 --> 00:15:44,800
...when you saw us over the wall
and longed to be with us...

133
00:15:45,040 --> 00:15:50,600
...that didn't mean you were prepared
for the way we live here, did it?

134
00:15:50,840 --> 00:15:53,120
No, Mother, but I pray and I try.

135
00:15:53,360 --> 00:15:55,000
And I am learning. I really am.

136
00:15:55,240 --> 00:15:58,200
What is the most important lesson
you have learned here?

137
00:15:58,440 --> 00:16:03,560
To find out what is the will of God
and do it wholeheartedly.

138
00:16:04,800 --> 00:16:07,080
Maria...

139
00:16:07,320 --> 00:16:10,000
...it seems to be God's will
that you leave us.

140
00:16:10,240 --> 00:16:11,920
- Leave?
- Only for a while.

141
00:16:12,160 --> 00:16:14,400
No, Mother!
Please don't send me away!

142
00:16:14,640 --> 00:16:19,120
This is where I belong. It's my home,
my family. It's my life.

143
00:16:19,360 --> 00:16:22,200
- Are you truly ready for it?
- Yes, I am.

144
00:16:22,440 --> 00:16:27,160
If you go out into the world for a
time, knowing what we expect of you...

145
00:16:27,400 --> 00:16:30,000
...you will find out
if you can expect it of yourself.

146
00:16:30,240 --> 00:16:35,840
I know what you expect, Mother,
and I can do it! I promise I can!

147
00:16:37,760 --> 00:16:40,440
Yes, Mother.

148
00:16:40,960 --> 00:16:44,040
If it is God's will.

149
00:16:44,720 --> 00:16:49,600
There is a family near Salzburg that
needs a governess until September.

150
00:16:49,840 --> 00:16:52,320
- September?
- For seven children.

151
00:16:52,560 --> 00:16:53,560
Seven children?!

152
00:16:53,800 --> 00:16:55,520
Do you like children?

153
00:16:55,760 --> 00:16:58,360
Well, yes, but seven!

154
00:16:58,600 --> 00:17:01,920
I will tell Captain von Trapp
to expect you tomorrow.

155
00:17:02,160 --> 00:17:03,920
Captain?

156
00:17:04,160 --> 00:17:08,800
A retired officer of the lmperial
Navy. A fine man and a brave one.

157
00:17:09,040 --> 00:17:11,600
His wife died,
and he is alone with the children.

158
00:17:11,840 --> 00:17:16,480
I understand he has had a difficult
time keeping a governess there.

159
00:17:16,720 --> 00:17:20,000
Why difficult, Reverend Mother?

160
00:17:20,240 --> 00:17:24,520
The Lord will show you
in His own good time.

161
00:17:58,360 --> 00:18:00,720
When the Lord closes a door...

162
00:18:00,960 --> 00:18:04,840
...somewhere He opens a window.

163
00:18:05,640 --> 00:18:10,400
<i>What will this day be like?</i>

164
00:18:10,640 --> 00:18:14,240
<i>I wonder</i>

165
00:18:19,000 --> 00:18:23,520
<i>What will my future be?</i>

166
00:18:23,760 --> 00:18:27,400
<i>I wonder</i>

167
00:18:27,440 --> 00:18:30,320
<i>It could be so exciting</i>

168
00:18:30,560 --> 00:18:33,520
<i>To be out in the world</i>
<i>To be free</i>

169
00:18:33,760 --> 00:18:37,600
<i>My heart should be wildly rejoicing</i>

170
00:18:37,840 --> 00:18:43,040
<i>Oh, what's the matter with me?</i>

171
00:18:43,280 --> 00:18:46,200
<i>I've always longed for adventure</i>

172
00:18:46,440 --> 00:18:49,880
<i>To do the things I've never dared</i>

173
00:18:50,120 --> 00:18:53,200
<i>Now here I'm facing adventure</i>

174
00:18:53,440 --> 00:19:00,800
<i>Then why am I so scared?</i>

175
00:19:02,640 --> 00:19:05,400
<i>A captain with seven children</i>

176
00:19:05,640 --> 00:19:09,840
<i>What's so fearsome about that?</i>

177
00:19:10,800 --> 00:19:13,280
<i>I must stop these doubts and worries</i>

178
00:19:13,520 --> 00:19:16,280
<i>If I don't I just know I'll turn back</i>

179
00:19:16,520 --> 00:19:20,320
<i>I must dream of the things</i>
<i>I am seeking</i>

180
00:19:20,560 --> 00:19:26,040
<i>I am seeking the courage I lack</i>

181
00:19:26,280 --> 00:19:29,960
<i>The courage to serve them</i>
<i>With reliance</i>

182
00:19:30,200 --> 00:19:33,000
<i>Face my mistakes without defiance</i>

183
00:19:33,240 --> 00:19:34,880
<i>Show them I'm worthy</i>

184
00:19:35,120 --> 00:19:37,680
<i>And while I show them</i>

185
00:19:37,920 --> 00:19:41,520
<i>I'll show me</i>

186
00:19:41,760 --> 00:19:46,920
<i>So let them bring on</i>
<i>All their problems</i>

187
00:19:47,160 --> 00:19:50,280
<i>I'll do better than my best</i>

188
00:19:50,520 --> 00:19:53,480
<i>I have confidence</i>
<i>They'll put me to the test</i>

189
00:19:53,720 --> 00:19:57,000
<i>But I'll make them see</i>
<i>I have confidence in me</i>

190
00:19:57,240 --> 00:20:00,400
<i>Somehow I will impress them</i>

191
00:20:00,640 --> 00:20:03,760
<i>I will be firm but kind</i>

192
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:07,160
<i>And all those children</i>
<i>Heaven bless them</i>

193
00:20:07,400 --> 00:20:10,560
<i>They will look up to me</i>
<i>And mind me</i>

194
00:20:10,800 --> 00:20:13,800
<i>With each step I am more certain</i>

195
00:20:14,040 --> 00:20:17,120
<i>Everything will turn out fine</i>

196
00:20:17,360 --> 00:20:20,320
<i>I have confidence</i>
<i>The world can all be mine</i>

197
00:20:20,560 --> 00:20:27,320
<i>They'll have to agree</i>
<i>I have confidence in me</i>

198
00:20:27,320 --> 00:20:29,960
<i>I have confidence in sunshine</i>

199
00:20:30,200 --> 00:20:33,120
<i>I have confidence in rain</i>

200
00:20:33,360 --> 00:20:36,160
<i>I have confidence</i>
<i>That spring will come again</i>

201
00:20:36,400 --> 00:20:39,360
<i>Besides which you see</i>
<i>I have confidence in me</i>

202
00:20:39,600 --> 00:20:42,600
<i>Strength doesn't lie in numbers</i>

203
00:20:42,840 --> 00:20:45,760
<i>Strength doesn't lie in wealth</i>

204
00:20:46,000 --> 00:20:49,160
<i>Strength lies in nights</i>
<i>Of peaceful slumbers</i>

205
00:20:49,400 --> 00:20:52,200
<i>When you wake up, wake up</i>
<i>It's healthy</i>

206
00:20:52,440 --> 00:20:55,320
<i>All I trust I leave my heart to</i>

207
00:20:55,560 --> 00:20:58,320
<i>All I trust becomes my own</i>

208
00:20:58,560 --> 00:21:04,640
<i>I have confidence in confidence alone</i>

209
00:21:17,200 --> 00:21:20,240
Oh, help.

210
00:21:30,440 --> 00:21:37,320
<i>I have confidence in confidence alone</i>

211
00:21:37,560 --> 00:21:42,200
<i>Besides which you see</i>
<i>I have confidence...</i>

212
00:21:42,440 --> 00:21:49,400
<i>... in me</i>

213
00:21:51,840 --> 00:21:54,880
Oh. Whoo.

214
00:21:55,280 --> 00:21:59,040
Hello. Here I am.

215
00:22:00,240 --> 00:22:03,520
I'm from the convent.
I'm the new governess, captain.

216
00:22:03,640 --> 00:22:06,960
And I'm the old butler, frylein.

217
00:22:07,200 --> 00:22:08,360
Oh.

218
00:22:08,600 --> 00:22:11,840
Well, how do you do?

219
00:22:20,440 --> 00:22:25,840
You'll wait here, please.

220
00:23:47,160 --> 00:23:51,960
In future, remember certain rooms
in this house are not to be disturbed.

221
00:23:52,200 --> 00:23:55,120
Yes, captain, sir.

222
00:24:01,200 --> 00:24:07,200
- Why do you stare at me that way?
- You don't look like a sea captain.

223
00:24:07,440 --> 00:24:10,800
I'm afraid you don't look
very much like a governess.

224
00:24:11,040 --> 00:24:12,160
- Turn around.
- What?

225
00:24:12,400 --> 00:24:15,040
Turn.

226
00:24:16,640 --> 00:24:19,240
Hat off.

227
00:24:20,840 --> 00:24:23,360
Put on another dress
before meeting the children.

228
00:24:23,600 --> 00:24:25,160
But I don't have another.

229
00:24:25,400 --> 00:24:28,160
When we enter the abbey,
our worldly clothes go to the poor.

230
00:24:28,400 --> 00:24:29,560
What about this one?

231
00:24:29,800 --> 00:24:31,360
The poor didn't want it.

232
00:24:31,600 --> 00:24:32,600
Hm.

233
00:24:32,840 --> 00:24:37,160
There wasn't time to make a new dress.
I can make clothes.

234
00:24:37,400 --> 00:24:40,000
I'll see that you get some material.

235
00:24:40,240 --> 00:24:42,480
Today, if possible.

236
00:24:42,720 --> 00:24:44,400
- Now, frylein...
- Maria.

237
00:24:44,640 --> 00:24:47,200
- I don't know how much they told you.
- Not much.

238
00:24:47,440 --> 00:24:49,920
You are the twelfth governess...

239
00:24:50,160 --> 00:24:52,480
...to look after my children
since their mother died.

240
00:24:52,720 --> 00:24:54,840
I trust you will be an improvement
on the last one.

241
00:24:55,080 --> 00:24:58,320
She stayed only two hours.

242
00:24:58,480 --> 00:25:02,120
What's wrong with the children, sir?

243
00:25:02,360 --> 00:25:06,600
Nothing is wrong with the children,
only the governesses.

244
00:25:06,840 --> 00:25:12,200
They could not maintain discipline,
without which the house cannot be run.

245
00:25:12,440 --> 00:25:14,200
Drill them in their studies.

246
00:25:14,440 --> 00:25:17,800
I will not permit them to dream
away their summer holidays.

247
00:25:18,040 --> 00:25:20,600
Each afternoon,
they march, breathing deeply.

248
00:25:20,840 --> 00:25:22,400
Bedtime is to be strictly observed.

249
00:25:22,640 --> 00:25:23,520
When do they play?

250
00:25:23,760 --> 00:25:27,640
You will see to it that they conduct
themselves with the utmost decorum.

251
00:25:27,880 --> 00:25:32,200
- I am placing you in command.
- Yes, sir.

252
00:26:48,040 --> 00:26:49,480
Now...

253
00:26:49,720 --> 00:26:54,040
...this is your new governess,
Frylein Maria.

254
00:26:54,160 --> 00:26:56,120
Give your name at your signal.

255
00:26:56,360 --> 00:27:00,040
Frylein, listen carefully. Learn
their signals so you can call them.

256
00:27:01,600 --> 00:27:02,960
Liesl.

257
00:27:03,200 --> 00:27:04,880
Friedrich.

258
00:27:05,120 --> 00:27:06,600
Louisa.

259
00:27:06,840 --> 00:27:08,040
Kurt.

260
00:27:08,280 --> 00:27:09,280
Brigitta.

261
00:27:09,520 --> 00:27:10,760
Marta.

262
00:27:16,880 --> 00:27:19,640
Gretl.

263
00:27:22,600 --> 00:27:25,880
Now, let's see how well you listened.

264
00:27:26,120 --> 00:27:28,400
I won't need to whistle for them,
Reverend Captain.

265
00:27:28,640 --> 00:27:31,920
I mean, I'll use their names.
Such lovely names.

266
00:27:32,160 --> 00:27:35,200
Frylein, this is a large house.
The grounds are extensive.

267
00:27:35,440 --> 00:27:38,080
And I will not have anyone shouting.

268
00:27:38,320 --> 00:27:39,920
You will take this, please.
Learn to use it.

269
00:27:40,160 --> 00:27:43,240
The children will help you.

270
00:27:43,720 --> 00:27:48,120
Now, when I want you,
this is what you will hear.

271
00:27:48,360 --> 00:27:50,720
Oh, no, sir. I'm sorry, sir!

272
00:27:50,960 --> 00:27:52,400
I could never answer to a whistle.

273
00:27:52,640 --> 00:27:55,160
Whistles are for animals,
not for children.

274
00:27:55,400 --> 00:27:57,360
And definitely not for me.

275
00:27:57,600 --> 00:28:00,680
It would be too humiliating.

276
00:28:00,920 --> 00:28:05,960
Frylein, were you this much trouble
at the abbey?

277
00:28:06,200 --> 00:28:08,760
Oh, much more, sir.

278
00:28:17,920 --> 00:28:20,600
I don't know your signal.

279
00:28:20,840 --> 00:28:24,840
You may call me "captain".

280
00:28:35,760 --> 00:28:38,640
At ease.

281
00:28:39,840 --> 00:28:41,320
Now that there's just us...

282
00:28:41,560 --> 00:28:45,800
...would you please tell me all your
names again and how old you are.

283
00:28:46,040 --> 00:28:50,360
I'm Liesl. I'm 16 years old,
and I don't need a governess.

284
00:28:50,600 --> 00:28:55,040
I'm glad you told me, Liesl.
We'll just be good friends.

285
00:28:55,600 --> 00:28:59,280
I'm Friedrich. I'm 14.
I'm impossible.

286
00:28:59,520 --> 00:29:01,120
Really? Who told you that, Friedrich?

287
00:29:01,360 --> 00:29:04,920
Frylein Josephine.
Four governesses ago.

288
00:29:05,160 --> 00:29:08,040
I'm Brigitta.

289
00:29:08,320 --> 00:29:12,600
You didn't tell me how old you are,
Louisa.

290
00:29:12,840 --> 00:29:15,000
I'm Brigitta. She's Louisa.

291
00:29:15,240 --> 00:29:17,880
She's 13 years old, and you're smart.

292
00:29:18,120 --> 00:29:21,800
I'm 10, and I think your dress
is the ugliest one I ever saw.

293
00:29:22,040 --> 00:29:24,520
- Brigitta, you shouldn't say that.
- Why not?

294
00:29:24,760 --> 00:29:26,960
- Don't you think it's ugly?
- Of course.

295
00:29:27,200 --> 00:29:29,800
But Frylein Helga's was ugliest.

296
00:29:30,040 --> 00:29:32,560
I'm Kurt. I'm 11.
I'm incorrigible.

297
00:29:32,800 --> 00:29:35,800
- Congratulations.
- What's "incorrigible"?

298
00:29:36,040 --> 00:29:41,240
I think it means you want
to be treated like a boy.

299
00:29:41,840 --> 00:29:45,000
I'm Marta, and I'm going to be
seven on Tuesday.

300
00:29:45,240 --> 00:29:47,480
I'd like a pink parasol.

301
00:29:47,720 --> 00:29:50,680
Pink's my favorite color too.

302
00:29:51,440 --> 00:29:53,200
Yes, you're Gretl.

303
00:29:53,440 --> 00:29:55,280
And you're five years old?

304
00:29:55,520 --> 00:29:58,920
My, you're practically a lady.

305
00:29:59,840 --> 00:30:03,880
I have to tell you a secret.
I've never been a governess.

306
00:30:04,120 --> 00:30:06,800
You don't know anything
about being a governess?

307
00:30:07,040 --> 00:30:09,000
Nothing. I'll need lots of advice.

308
00:30:09,240 --> 00:30:13,600
The best way to start is to tell
Father to mind his own business.

309
00:30:13,840 --> 00:30:15,520
Never come to dinner on time.

310
00:30:15,760 --> 00:30:18,400
Never eat your soup quietly.

311
00:30:18,640 --> 00:30:20,600
During dessert, always blow your nose.

312
00:30:20,840 --> 00:30:23,480
Don't you believe a word they say,
Frylein Maria.

313
00:30:23,720 --> 00:30:27,480
- Oh, why not?
- Because I like you.

314
00:30:27,720 --> 00:30:29,600
Children, outside for your walk.

315
00:30:29,840 --> 00:30:31,600
Father's orders. Hurry up.

316
00:30:31,840 --> 00:30:33,080
Quick, quick, quick.

317
00:30:33,320 --> 00:30:36,400
Frylein Maria, I'm Frau Schmidt,
the housekeeper.

318
00:30:36,640 --> 00:30:37,600
How do you do.

319
00:30:37,840 --> 00:30:42,040
I'll show you to your room.
Follow me.

320
00:30:51,240 --> 00:30:54,400
Poor little dears.

321
00:31:05,120 --> 00:31:10,760
You're very lucky. With
Frylein Helga it was a snake.

322
00:31:22,640 --> 00:31:25,000
Good evening.

323
00:31:25,240 --> 00:31:28,640
- Good evening, children.
- Good evening, Frylein Maria.

324
00:31:35,560 --> 00:31:37,120
Enchanting little ritual.

325
00:31:37,360 --> 00:31:40,880
Something you learned at the abbey?

326
00:31:41,120 --> 00:31:44,800
No.

327
00:31:44,920 --> 00:31:47,640
Rheumatism.

328
00:31:55,520 --> 00:32:00,040
Excuse me, captain. Haven't we
forgotten to thank the Lord?

329
00:32:06,440 --> 00:32:09,600
For what we receive,
may the Lord make us truly thankful.

330
00:32:09,840 --> 00:32:13,160
- Amen.
Amen.

331
00:32:16,040 --> 00:32:17,840
I'd like to thank you all...

332
00:32:18,080 --> 00:32:22,440
...for the precious gift
you left in my pocket today.

333
00:32:24,280 --> 00:32:27,520
What gift?

334
00:32:29,040 --> 00:32:31,080
It's a secret between
the children and me.

335
00:32:31,320 --> 00:32:34,960
Then I suggest you keep it,
and let us eat.

336
00:32:35,200 --> 00:32:37,080
Knowing how nervous
I must have been...

337
00:32:37,320 --> 00:32:39,600
...a stranger in a new household...

338
00:32:39,840 --> 00:32:42,800
...knowing how important it was
for me to feel accepted...

339
00:32:43,040 --> 00:32:47,040
...it was so kind and thoughtful of
you to make my first moments here...

340
00:32:47,280 --> 00:32:49,400
...so warm and happy...

341
00:32:49,640 --> 00:32:52,800
...and pleasant.

342
00:33:00,200 --> 00:33:03,640
- What is the matter, Marta?
- Nothing.

343
00:33:14,040 --> 00:33:15,040
Frylein...

344
00:33:15,280 --> 00:33:18,920
...is it to be at every meal
or merely at dinnertime...

345
00:33:19,160 --> 00:33:23,520
...that you intend leading us through
this rare and wonderful new world...

346
00:33:23,760 --> 00:33:26,840
...of indigestion?

347
00:33:26,840 --> 00:33:31,040
They're all right, captain.
They're just happy.

348
00:33:47,560 --> 00:33:50,160
- Rolf, good evening.
- Good evening, Franz.

349
00:33:50,400 --> 00:33:53,000
- I trust everything is under control?
- Yes, yes.

350
00:33:53,240 --> 00:33:54,320
Good.

351
00:33:54,560 --> 00:33:56,880
- Are there any developments?
- Perhaps.

352
00:33:57,120 --> 00:33:59,200
- Is the captain home?
- He's at dinner.

353
00:33:59,440 --> 00:34:01,680
- With the family?
- Yes.

354
00:34:01,920 --> 00:34:04,120
Give him this telegram at once.

355
00:34:04,360 --> 00:34:06,840
Certainly.

356
00:34:16,560 --> 00:34:19,720
A telegram for you, sir.

357
00:34:20,960 --> 00:34:22,760
Franz? Who delivered it?

358
00:34:23,000 --> 00:34:26,440
That young lad Rolf, of course.

359
00:34:27,200 --> 00:34:29,560
- Father, may I be excused?
Hm.

360
00:34:29,800 --> 00:34:34,120
Children, in the morning I shall
be going to Vienna.

361
00:34:34,360 --> 00:34:38,200
Not again, Father!

362
00:34:40,440 --> 00:34:42,800
How long will you be gone this time?

363
00:34:43,040 --> 00:34:44,400
I'm not sure, Gretl.

364
00:34:44,640 --> 00:34:48,760
- To visit Baroness Schraeder again?
- Mind your own business!

365
00:34:49,000 --> 00:34:52,320
As a matter of fact, yes, Louisa.

366
00:34:52,560 --> 00:34:56,240
- Why can't we ever see the baroness?
Why would she want to see you?

367
00:34:56,480 --> 00:35:01,160
You are going to see the baroness.
I'm bringing her back with me to visit.

368
00:35:01,400 --> 00:35:02,400
Good.

369
00:35:02,640 --> 00:35:04,320
And Uncle Max.

370
00:35:04,560 --> 00:35:08,400
Uncle Max!

371
00:35:22,320 --> 00:35:25,040
Rolf!

372
00:35:26,520 --> 00:35:29,000
Oh, Rolf!

373
00:35:30,000 --> 00:35:32,800
- No, Liesl. We mustn't!
- Why not, silly?

374
00:35:33,040 --> 00:35:35,560
- I don't know...
- Isn't this why you're waiting?

375
00:35:35,800 --> 00:35:37,560
Yes, of course.

376
00:35:37,800 --> 00:35:40,480
- I've missed you, Liesl.
- You have? How much?

377
00:35:40,720 --> 00:35:44,400
I even thought of sending a telegram,
so I'd be able to deliver it here.

378
00:35:44,640 --> 00:35:48,360
Oh, that's a lovely thought!
Why don't you, right now?

379
00:35:48,600 --> 00:35:52,600
- But I'm here!
- Please, Rolf. Send me a telegram.

380
00:35:52,840 --> 00:35:56,560
I'll start it for you.
"Dear Liesl..."

381
00:35:56,800 --> 00:36:00,240
"Dear Liesl: I'd like to be able
to tell you...

382
00:36:00,480 --> 00:36:02,600
...how I feel about you. Stop."

383
00:36:02,840 --> 00:36:07,160
"Unfortunately, this wire
is already too expensive."

384
00:36:07,400 --> 00:36:08,720
"Sincerely, Rolf."

385
00:36:08,960 --> 00:36:11,560
- "Sincerely"?
- Cordially.

386
00:36:11,800 --> 00:36:14,960
- "Cordially"?
- Affectionately?

387
00:36:15,200 --> 00:36:16,360
Mmm.

388
00:36:16,600 --> 00:36:19,560
Will there be any reply?

389
00:36:19,800 --> 00:36:22,600
"Dear Rolf: Stop."

390
00:36:22,840 --> 00:36:27,320
"Don't stop! Your Liesl."

391
00:36:27,440 --> 00:36:31,160
If only we didn't have to wait
for someone to send Father a telegram.

392
00:36:31,400 --> 00:36:34,320
How do I know when I'll see you again?

393
00:36:34,560 --> 00:36:37,240
Well, let's see...

394
00:36:38,640 --> 00:36:41,200
I could come here by mistake.

395
00:36:41,440 --> 00:36:46,560
With a telegram for Colonel Schneider!
He's here from Berlin staying with...

396
00:36:46,800 --> 00:36:49,960
No one knows he's here.
Don't tell your father.

397
00:36:50,200 --> 00:36:53,200
- Why not?
- Your father's so Austrian.

398
00:36:53,440 --> 00:36:54,640
We're all Austrian.

399
00:36:54,880 --> 00:36:59,080
Some think we ought to be German, and
they're very mad at those who don't.

400
00:36:59,320 --> 00:37:02,520
They're getting ready to...

401
00:37:02,640 --> 00:37:04,960
Let's hope your father
doesn't get into trouble.

402
00:37:05,200 --> 00:37:09,920
Don't worry. He's a big naval hero.
He was even decorated by the emperor.

403
00:37:10,160 --> 00:37:13,560
I don't worry about him.
I worry about his daughter.

404
00:37:13,800 --> 00:37:15,200
Me? Why?

405
00:37:15,440 --> 00:37:17,120
- Well, you're so...
- What?

406
00:37:17,360 --> 00:37:19,000
You're such a baby!

407
00:37:19,240 --> 00:37:23,520
I'm 16.
What's such a baby about that?

408
00:37:24,200 --> 00:37:27,560
<i>You wait, little girl</i>
<i>On an empty stage</i>

409
00:37:27,800 --> 00:37:31,400
<i>For fate to turn the light on</i>

410
00:37:31,640 --> 00:37:34,760
<i>Your life, little girl</i>
<i>Is an empty page</i>

411
00:37:35,000 --> 00:37:39,360
<i>That men will want to write on</i>

412
00:37:39,600 --> 00:37:45,520
<i>To write on</i>

413
00:37:45,760 --> 00:37:49,480
<i>You are 16 going on 17</i>

414
00:37:49,720 --> 00:37:53,320
<i>Baby, it's time to think</i>

415
00:37:53,560 --> 00:37:57,080
<i>Better beware</i>
<i>Be canny and careful</i>

416
00:37:57,320 --> 00:38:00,880
<i>Baby, you're on the brink</i>

417
00:38:01,120 --> 00:38:04,760
<i>You are 16 going on 17</i>

418
00:38:05,000 --> 00:38:08,560
<i>Fellows will fall in line</i>

419
00:38:08,800 --> 00:38:11,960
<i>Eager young lads</i>
<i>And roués and cads</i>

420
00:38:12,200 --> 00:38:15,960
<i>Will offer you food and wine</i>

421
00:38:16,200 --> 00:38:20,000
<i>Totally unprepared are you</i>

422
00:38:20,240 --> 00:38:23,960
<i>To face a world of men</i>

423
00:38:24,200 --> 00:38:28,200
<i>Timid and shy and scared are you</i>

424
00:38:28,440 --> 00:38:31,800
<i>Of things beyond your ken</i>

425
00:38:32,040 --> 00:38:35,720
<i>You need someone older and wiser</i>

426
00:38:35,960 --> 00:38:39,680
<i>Telling you what to do</i>

427
00:38:39,920 --> 00:38:43,200
<i>I am 17 going on 18</i>

428
00:38:43,440 --> 00:38:50,640
<i>I'll take care of you</i>

429
00:39:20,320 --> 00:39:23,520
<i>I am 16 going on 17</i>

430
00:39:23,760 --> 00:39:27,000
<i>I know that I'm naive</i>

431
00:39:27,240 --> 00:39:30,320
<i>Fellows I meet</i>
<i>May tell me I'm sweet</i>

432
00:39:30,560 --> 00:39:34,320
<i>And willingly I believe</i>

433
00:39:34,560 --> 00:39:37,600
<i>I am 16 going on 17</i>

434
00:39:37,840 --> 00:39:41,400
<i>Innocent as a rose</i>

435
00:39:41,640 --> 00:39:44,960
<i>Bachelor dandies</i>
<i>Drinkers of brandies</i>

436
00:39:45,200 --> 00:39:48,400
<i>What do I know of those?</i>

437
00:39:48,640 --> 00:39:52,000
<i>Totally unprepared am I</i>

438
00:39:52,240 --> 00:39:55,800
<i>To face a world of men</i>

439
00:39:56,040 --> 00:39:59,200
<i>Timid and shy and scared am I</i>

440
00:39:59,440 --> 00:40:03,200
<i>Of things beyond my ken</i>

441
00:40:03,440 --> 00:40:06,880
<i>I need someone older and wiser</i>

442
00:40:07,120 --> 00:40:10,400
<i>Telling me what to do</i>

443
00:40:10,640 --> 00:40:14,120
<i>You are 17 going on 18</i>

444
00:40:14,360 --> 00:40:21,280
<i>I'll depend on you</i>

445
00:41:57,440 --> 00:42:00,880
Whee!

446
00:42:08,240 --> 00:42:10,320
Come in.

447
00:42:10,560 --> 00:42:13,640
Frau Schmidt.

448
00:42:14,360 --> 00:42:16,080
For your new dresses.

449
00:42:16,320 --> 00:42:20,200
- The captain had these sent from town.
- Oh, how lovely!

450
00:42:20,440 --> 00:42:23,760
These will make the prettiest
clothes I've ever had.

451
00:42:24,000 --> 00:42:27,360
Do you think he would
get me more material if I asked?

452
00:42:27,600 --> 00:42:31,080
- How many dresses do you need?
- Not for me, for the children.

453
00:42:31,320 --> 00:42:33,280
I want to make them some play clothes.

454
00:42:33,520 --> 00:42:37,160
The von Trapp children don't play.
They march.

455
00:42:37,400 --> 00:42:40,480
Surely you don't approve of that.

456
00:42:40,720 --> 00:42:43,000
Ever since the captain
lost his poor wife...

457
00:42:43,240 --> 00:42:46,400
...he runs this house as if on
one of his ships.

458
00:42:46,640 --> 00:42:47,960
Whistles, orders.

459
00:42:48,200 --> 00:42:50,000
No more music, no more laughing.

460
00:42:50,240 --> 00:42:53,880
Nothing that reminds him of her.
Even the children.

461
00:42:54,120 --> 00:42:55,720
But that's so wrong.

462
00:42:55,960 --> 00:42:57,400
Oh, well.

463
00:42:57,640 --> 00:43:01,160
How do you like your room?
There'll be new drapes at the windows.

464
00:43:01,400 --> 00:43:02,600
Bu these are fine.

465
00:43:02,840 --> 00:43:04,360
New ones have been ordered.

466
00:43:04,600 --> 00:43:07,800
- But I really don't need them.
- Good night, now.

467
00:43:08,040 --> 00:43:11,920
Frau Schmidt, if I asked
the captain about the material...?

468
00:43:12,160 --> 00:43:16,760
- He's leaving in the morning.
- Of course. How long will he be gone?

469
00:43:17,000 --> 00:43:22,280
It depends. The last time he visited
the baroness, he stayed for a month.

470
00:43:22,520 --> 00:43:26,920
I shouldn't be saying this to you.
I don't know you that well.

471
00:43:27,160 --> 00:43:29,920
But if you ask me,
the captain's thinking seriously...

472
00:43:30,160 --> 00:43:32,280
...of marrying her before
summer's over.

473
00:43:32,520 --> 00:43:36,800
Wonderful! The children will
have a mother again.

474
00:43:37,040 --> 00:43:38,280
Yes.

475
00:43:38,520 --> 00:43:40,160
Well, good night.

476
00:43:40,400 --> 00:43:43,240
Good night.

477
00:43:59,400 --> 00:44:02,120
Dear Father, now I know
why You sent me here.

478
00:44:02,360 --> 00:44:05,120
To help these children
prepare for a new mother.

479
00:44:05,360 --> 00:44:08,480
And I pray this will become
a happy family in Thy sight.

480
00:44:08,720 --> 00:44:11,680
God bless the captain.
God bless Liesl and Friedrich.

481
00:44:11,920 --> 00:44:15,960
God bless Louisa, Brigitta,
Marta and little Gretl.

482
00:44:16,200 --> 00:44:20,400
And I forgot the other boy.
What's his name?

483
00:44:20,560 --> 00:44:22,280
Well, God bless what's-his-name.

484
00:44:22,520 --> 00:44:26,400
God bless the Reverend Mother
and Sister Margaretta...

485
00:44:26,640 --> 00:44:28,280
...and everybody at the abbey.

486
00:44:28,520 --> 00:44:31,160
And now, dear God, about Liesl.

487
00:44:31,400 --> 00:44:33,160
Help her know that I'm her friend...

488
00:44:33,400 --> 00:44:36,320
...and help her tell me
what she's been up to.

489
00:44:36,560 --> 00:44:37,720
- Are you going to tell on me?
- Shh.

490
00:44:37,960 --> 00:44:41,240
Help me to be understanding
so I may guide her footsteps.

491
00:44:41,480 --> 00:44:44,000
In the name of the Father,
the Son and the Holy Ghost.

492
00:44:44,240 --> 00:44:47,120
I was out walking
and somebody locked the doors early.

493
00:44:47,360 --> 00:44:52,360
I didn't want to wake everybody,
so when I saw your window open...

494
00:44:52,400 --> 00:44:55,880
You're not going to tell Father,
are you?

495
00:44:56,120 --> 00:44:58,840
Hm.

496
00:45:01,200 --> 00:45:02,680
How did you climb up?

497
00:45:02,920 --> 00:45:05,880
It's how we always got in
to play tricks on the governess.

498
00:45:06,120 --> 00:45:09,720
Louisa can make it with
a whole jar of spiders in her hand.

499
00:45:09,960 --> 00:45:12,280
Spiders?

500
00:45:12,520 --> 00:45:14,880
Oh. Liesl.

501
00:45:15,120 --> 00:45:19,120
Were you out walking all by yourself?

502
00:45:24,800 --> 00:45:28,760
If we wash that dress tonight,
nobody would notice it tomorrow.

503
00:45:29,000 --> 00:45:32,200
You could put this on.

504
00:45:32,360 --> 00:45:34,920
Take your dress and put it
to soak in the bathtub.

505
00:45:35,160 --> 00:45:39,560
Come back here and sit on the bed,
and we'll have a talk.

506
00:45:39,800 --> 00:45:42,680
I told you today
I didn't need a governess.

507
00:45:42,920 --> 00:45:46,400
Well, maybe I do.

508
00:46:14,160 --> 00:46:16,520
Gretl, are you scared?

509
00:46:19,960 --> 00:46:22,120
You're not frightened
of a storm, are you?

510
00:46:22,360 --> 00:46:25,440
You just stay right here with me.

511
00:46:25,680 --> 00:46:31,200
- Where are the others?
- They're asleep. They're not scared.

512
00:46:33,960 --> 00:46:37,200
Oh, no? Look.

513
00:46:37,200 --> 00:46:39,080
All right, up here on the bed.

514
00:46:39,320 --> 00:46:42,760
- Really?
- Well, just this once. Come on.

515
00:46:43,000 --> 00:46:48,640
- Now we'll wait for the boys.
- You won't see them. Boys are brave.

516
00:46:53,000 --> 00:46:54,960
You weren't scared, were you?

517
00:46:55,200 --> 00:46:59,120
Oh, no. We just wanted
to be sure that you weren't.

518
00:46:59,360 --> 00:47:02,280
- That's very thoughtful of you.
It wasn't my idea.

519
00:47:02,520 --> 00:47:04,280
It was Kurt's!

520
00:47:04,520 --> 00:47:08,520
Kurt! That's the one I left out!
God bless Kurt.

521
00:47:09,720 --> 00:47:11,400
Why does it do that?

522
00:47:11,640 --> 00:47:15,320
The lightning talks to the thunder,
and the thunder answers.

523
00:47:15,560 --> 00:47:17,960
- But lightning must be nasty.
- Not really.

